Terminology [ edit source ]

This section defines the terminology which we use for the discussion of this experiment.

Outcome [ edit source ]

Outcome is the number of tokens that the user receives according to each party's research.

Two side effects of how the research is structured can be seen:

1. There can be groups which gained/lost token, but no outcome is given in the data.

However, this is OK, especially in designs where there are many proposals and not many parties.

For example: there are 3 groups in each scenario. Each has 10 people, and you have 3 proposals. Each proposal affects 2 of them.

Moreover, a third of the time, the 2 parties do not agree that this outcome is still the best, and another third of the time, they do agree.

With such a design, there are 2 parties which agree with each other about some proportion, and disagree with their aligned partners about the same proportion.

However, we cannot say exactly in which proportion each of these situations occurred.

Read NCId.score.score as C if the 2 parties aligned and as never aligned otherwise.

Read NCId.gather.gather.collect to see which parties/gatherings are aligned against which.

2. There are groups which are out of half of all scenarios; but exactly one outcome is given for each of those groups.

Notice that, to counter this, the outcome and pattern, a "weighted score" is also given, as explained below.

Weighted score [ edit source ]

The weighted score is the result of multiplying the frequency of appearance of a party, with the outcome of the outcome of dividing by that entity.

This is needed to overcome slight imbalances, by consistency.

Minor ruleballing [ edit source ]

Minor ruleballing is OK, because:

- This was designed to reduce the number of RATs;
- There are several parties and groups. To have optimal equality of lightness and darkness in the room, this needed a third party;
- It needs more than 3 groups to have in total meaningful considerations.

This tutorial is a "brain-storming notebook" to create some examples. All silly for teaching the concept of how R queries a SQL database and can connect and see individual records.

We used to do this with GROUP BY, but that shifted nicely to .group_by (dbplyr::dplyr::.group_by) which is so much more expressive. During testing I saw that dplyr::score() sugar lagged behind so I went ahead and added a few bells and whistles to make the experience comparable as much as possible. The incentive here is to sweat / stress the SQL database and the helper functions to see if there are any little quirks or annoyances with performance. During testing I only threw out a few headache fixes as the proposed code was running much faster than existing defaults.

The motivation for this tutorial was to cleanly and clearly see how in a relational database you relatively easily can get distributions out of quantiles or frequency counts to add as columns to a results table. With some helper functions added to dbplyr or dplyr a lot of the mental overhead and logic can be translated into https://github.com/wilkelab/dplyr/wiki/The- `{% endif parser %}`%(^` {% comment parser %}`
